Release engineering ticket. Our runtime-greeter artifact is meant to be a multi-release JAR: Java 8 consumers get the base service provider, while Java 11 and newer consumers get the optimized provider with the same class name. The current build succeeds, but its packaging step puts the compiled source sets in the wrong place. That makes the artifact unusable on the oldest supported runtime and prevents multi-release lookup from selecting the intended implementation.

Repair the packaging without changing the Java API or provider names. The finished `build/libs/runtime-greeter.jar` must have all of these properties:

- the Java 8 `com/acme/greeter/RuntimeGreeting.class` is at the JAR root and has class-file major version 52;
- the Java 11 class with that same binary name is at `META-INF/versions/11/com/acme/greeter/RuntimeGreeting.class` and has class-file major version 55;
- the manifest retains `Multi-Release: true`;
- `META-INF/services/com.acme.greeter.GreetingService` remains at the JAR root with the configured provider, so `ServiceLoader` works in both runtime views;
- selecting the Java 8 view prints `base-java8`, while selecting the Java 11 view prints `version-java11`; and
- rebuilding the same checkout produces the same JAR bytes.

Keep the build dependency-free and offline: only the JDK, POSIX shell, and Python standard library are used. Do not edit `tests/verify.py`. Run `python3 tests/verify.py` to exercise the complete release check. The verifier provides its own deterministic offline JDK test double, so the check does not require a system JDK installation.
